    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <opener><salute>Dear Sir</salute></opener>
                <p>I have no scruple of taking y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> duplicates: but wish an acc<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>
                    cd be kept of what we pay for. I am not in the way of getting <persName ref="pe0402">Hollars</persName>.
                    you are <sic>pray buy for</sic> his <placeName ref="pl1379">Queenborough</placeName>, <placeName ref="pl1380">Dorchester</placeName> &amp; <rs type="art" ref="ar1046">cows</rs>. &amp; Be so good as to ask the price of his <rs type="art" ref="ar1047">5 <placeName ref="pl1381">Dovers</placeName></rs>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Y<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> most truely<lb/>
                        <persName ref="pe0232">TP.</persName></salute>
                    <dateline>April 17<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 81<note type="editorial">Richard Bull has added the year '81' to the date given by Pennant. The contents, together with the possibility that Bull may have confused the figures '1' and '7', suggests that 1787 is the probable date of this letter.</note></dateline>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>I wish a few rich men w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> join in printing 100 Copies of my <bibl type="editorial"><title ref="bi0475">outlines</title></bibl>.
                    I tho not <hi rend="underline">very</hi> rich w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> buy my part.</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
            <div>
                <p><address>
                    <addrLine><persName ref="pe0313">Mr Bull</persName> | <placeName ref="pl0759">Stratton street</placeName></addrLine>
                        <addrLine/>
                    </address></p>
            </div>
